Joint Message
from the Chair of the Board and the Interim President & CEO

The year 2025 was one of significant challenge and progress for VIA Rail.
Against a backdrop of economic uncertainty, geopolitical tension and shifting travel patterns, we were reminded that strong national institutions matter.
Passenger rail remains one of the few
services that physically links Canadians across vast distances, strengthening our sense of shared purpose.

MESSAGES FROM OUR LEADERS	VIA RAIL – 2025 ANNUAL REPORT	 	17






This commitment to national connection was especially evident through the Government of Canada’s Canada Strong Pass, which encouraged young people and families to explore the country by rail. Seeing thousands of new travellers step aboard, many experiencing train travel for the first time, was inspiring. Their journeys served as a reminder that rail continues to bring Canadians together, whether discovering unfamiliar regions or reconnecting with familiar ones. We look forward to welcoming even more Canadians in 2026 as the program continues.
In 2025, VIA Rail completed the full commissioning of its new Corridor fleet, one of the largest and most complex modernization initiatives in our history. A transformation
of this scale inevitably brings challenges. Mechanical issues and speed restrictions impacted punctuality and reliability, and we recognize the inconvenience this caused our passengers. Amid the operational pressures of a complex fleet transition, our employees supported customers with professionalism and care, exemplifying the steady, human mindset that defines VIA Rail at its best.
Together, the Board and Executive team are addressing these challenges with discipline and clarity. Some of the pressures we face, particularly from operating primarily on infrastructure we do not own, are longstanding. But many aspects of our performance are within our control, and together we are taking a hard look at what must improve. With the commissioning phase now complete, our focus has shifted fully to stabilization, performance optimization, and continuous improvement.

Despite these operational pressures, revenues increased and our deficit narrowed, results achieved through disciplined management and the dedication of our teams across the country. As the Corporation continues to modernize and rebuild ridership, responsible stewardship of public resources remains central to our mandate.
We would like to acknowledge the contributions of
VIA Rail’s previous CEO, Mario Péloquin, and thank him for his work during an important period in the Corporation’s evolution. As we move forward with renewed focus,
we are committed to ensuring stability and continuity. With a new interim CEO in place, the Board and Executive team share a unified view of the challenges ahead and the opportunities before us.
Among the opportunities that continue to shape our path, we advanced in 2025 with one of the most important procurements in VIA Rail’s history: a new fleet for our Long Distance, Regional and Remote services. By completing the Request for Qualifications and launching the Request for Proposals, we took critical steps toward renewing the trains that connect communities across the country.
Investments such as the modernization of the Toronto Maintenance Centre also advanced significantly this past year. When completed in 2026, this project will reinforce long-term fleet reliability, offering substantial benefits for the resilience of our operations.

MESSAGES FROM OUR LEADERS	VIA RAIL – 2025 ANNUAL REPORT	 	18






Constructive labour relations were another defining feature of 2025. VIA Rail reached new collective agreements
with Unifor, representing the majority of our workforce. This achievement reflects mutual respect, organizational stability, and a shared dedication to serving Canadians.
Throughout the year, Canadians reminded us how deeply they value passenger rail. This was especially visible during the milestone anniversaries marking The Ocean’s 120th year of service and The Canadian’s 70th. Thousands gathered in Halifax and Vancouver to share stories, tour the trains, and celebrate a shared legacy that spans generations and regions.
We thank the Government of Canada and the Ministers of Transport who served in 2025, Minister Anita Anand,
Minister Chrystia Freeland, and Minister Steven MacKinnon, for their support of VIA Rail and their commitment to passenger rail across Canada.
Above all, we want to thank VIA Rail’s 3,867 employees for their dedication, and our passengers for the trust they place in us.
Together, the Board and the Executive Team remain united in purpose. Our priorities are clear. We will stabilize performance, strengthen reliability, reinforce public confidence and continue building a passenger rail system that Canadians can depend on with pride for generations to come.


 	 
