Message from
the Chief Financial
and Technology Officer

The year 2025 required discipline and focus. In a constrained fiscal
environment, VIA Rail increased revenues to $514.8 million, up from $478.0 million the previous year, while reducing the operating loss to $375.7 million. These results reflect deliberate cost controls, strengthened financial oversight and a rigorous review of expenditures across the organization.

MESSAGES FROM OUR LEADERS	VIA RAIL – 2025 ANNUAL REPORT	 	20






As Chief Financial and Technology Officer, I am mindful that we are stewards of public funds, and I take that responsibility seriously. Throughout the year, I worked closely with our teams to ensure that every dollar supports service reliability, modernization and long-term sustainability, in alignment with the Government of Canada’s Comprehensive Expenditure Review, which called upon federally funded organizations to reduce operating spending. Under our VIAction 2030 Strategic Plan, VIA had already embarked on an ambitious operational review of all our activities to find savings, increase efficiencies and reduce our deficit. It is a program in which we will continually seek improvements.
Technology remains a key enabler of that progress.
In 2025, VIA Rail expanded the use of advanced analytics and artificial intelligence to optimize fuel consumption, one of its largest operating expenses. Strengthened asset management and improved operational efficiency are helping reduce costs while enhancing performance.
VIA Rail’s Corporate Project Management Office was honoured with the 2025 Elixir PMO of the Year Award from PMI-Montréal, recognizing disciplined governance and oversight of nearly 200 strategic projects nationwide. Strong project management remains essential to delivering modernization initiatives on time and on budget.

Capital investments continued in 2025, including the modernization of the Toronto Maintenance Centre and progress on procuring a new fleet for Long Distance, Regional and Remote services. These investments are guided by a clear objective: strengthening financial sustainability while supporting reliable service
for Canadians.
While ridership remained stable, encouraging trends
in revenue optimization emerged, including greater use of enhanced reservation tools and premium offerings.
VIA Rail’s customers remain loyal, and the Corporation
is confident that ridership will grow as reliability improves.
Operational performance and financial stewardship are inseparable. Reliability drives revenue. Discipline drives sustainability.
That discipline is not driven by finance alone. In 2025, VIA Rail introduced Innovia, a plaUorm designed to bring employees’ ideas forward and turn them into practical improvements across the organization. By empowering
teams to identify efficiencies, reduce waste and strengthen processes, Innovia strengthens a culture of continuous improvement. Many of the most meaningful gains in cost management and operational effectiveness begin with the people closest to the work, and this initiative reflects the Corporation’s commitment to harnessing that expertise.

