Directors’ Experience

The Board of VIA Rail brings together experienced and diverse leaders with expertise in corporate governance, government affairs, finance, project management, human resources, public policy, as well as risk management, safety and security. Their combined experience supports the Corporation’s strategic direction, in accordance with the Directors’ Competencies Policy.

Independence of the Board

The Board, with the exception of the President and CEO, operates independently from the Corporation’s management. This separation supports an effective governance model, with the Board holding management accountable for VIA Rail’s performance and routinely reviewing how responsibilities are allocated across the organization. The governance of Board activities and the definition of its powers are outlined in VIA Rail’s bylaws. The Board and Committee Charters further clarify governance roles and responsibilities and offer detailed guidelines on procedures.
Board and Committee meetings include in camera sessions, allowing directors to hold confidential discussions with the CEO, as well as separate sessions without the CEO. The Audit and Risk Committee also meets privately with representatives of the Office of the Auditor General of Canada, with VIA Rail's Chief Financial Officer, and Internal Auditor, and in camera as a Committee without the CEO.

Governance at Work

In 2025, the Board of Directors maintained steady oversight of VIA Rail’s performance, governance and long-term transformation. Throughout the year, it monitored operating and financial results against the Corporate
Plan and ensured transparent reporting and stewardship of public funds through regular quarterly reviews.
The Board also oversaw progress on the Corporation’s key modernization initiatives. This included continued advancement of the Corridor Fleet Replacement Program, with trainset deliveries and related capital deployment supporting the renewal of service in the Québec
City–Windsor Corridor. In parallel, the Board maintained oversight of long-distance fleet sustainment and reliability initiatives, including ongoing work related to the Legacy program and complementary measures aimed at improving fleet availability and operational resilience.
In addition to performance and capital oversight, the Board reinforced VIA Rail’s governance and compliance foundations. In 2025, the Corporation advanced its accessibility commitments, including the unveiling of its
2026–2029 Accessibility Plan submitted to the Government of Canada. The Board further supported the Corporation’s strategic direction by overseeing continued alignment
with VIA Rail’s long-term vision, including the evolution of VIAction 2030 as a guiding framework for priorities and outcomes.
The Board also continued to support VIA Rail’s role as a national institution, marking key milestones that underscored the Corporation’s enduring public value, such as the 120th anniversary of The Ocean and
the 70th anniversary of The Canadian.

