4.3	Operating Expenses (cont’d)
Total operating expenses increased by $26.1 million (9.8 percent) for the quarter and by $73.0 million (7.2 percent) for the year. The primary variances
are as follows:
Compensation and employee benefits
The expenses increased by $12.7 million (12.2 percent) during the quarter and by $20.3 million (5.1 percent) for the year. These increases are mainly due to higher
staffing costs associated with the annual salary increases and additional operational needs as well as an additional expense of $6.1 million due to an actuarial valuation in other employee benefit plans.
Train operations and fuel
The expenses increased by $1.5 million (3.0 percent) during the quarter and by $8.7 million (4.5 percent) for the year. These increases are mostly due to the disruptions in access.

Maintenance material
The expenses rose by $0.2 million (1.7 percent) compared to the last quarter and by $7.0 million (16.1 percent)
for the year. The increases are attributable to additional maintenance work resulting from higher equipment utilization, mainly driven by the greater number of Venture trainsets in service in the Corridor, as well
as to the additional repairs required on the aging non-Corridor fleet.
On-train product costs
The expenses increased by $0.9 million (7.6 percent) for the quarter and by $6.5 million (14.5 percent) for the year. The increases are primarily due to higher ridership in Business and Sleeper classes and higher prices reflecting current inflation rates. In addition, part of
the increase is linked to purchases related to the new Venture fleet.
Professional services
The expenses increased by $0.5 million (6.4 percent) during the quarter and by $6.1 million (33.0 percent) for the year. This increase reflects higher legal fees, mostly due to the disruptions in access.

