An impairment loss is recognized in net income and calculated as the difference between the carrying amount and the recoverable amount.

When there is a reversal of impairment loss, the carrying amount of the asset is increased to the lower of the recoverable amount and the carrying amount (net of depreciation or amortization) that the asset would have had if previous impairment loss had not been recognized. The reversal of impairment loss is recognized in the Statement of Comprehensive Income.
